vectorData.altText: That's right!  ’A’ is the lateral pterygoid plate. The pterygoid process consists of the lateral and medial pterygoid plates.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

the sphenoid bone (A), temporal bones (B) and occipital bone (C). Identify the pterygoid processes (D) of the sphenoid bone, each of which is composed of a medial (E) and lateral (F) pterygoid plate. Posterior to the medial pterygoid plate, identify the foramen lacerum     (G). Posterolateral to the lateral pterygoid plate, identify the foramen ovale     (H) and the foramen spinosum     (I). Use a pipe cleaner (NOT A PEN!!) to probe these foramina and observe their connections with the interior of the neurocranium. Continuing on the external surface of the skull base, medial to the foramen spinosum, identify the opening to the skeletal part of the auditory (pharyngotympanic or Eustacian     ) tube (J). In life, much of the wall of this tube is cartilaginous.
spiny, because it is situated just anterior to the spine of the sphenoid bone
Turn the skull over to identify the features on the inferior surface of the neurocranium.
named after Bartolomeo Eustachi, the Italian anatomist who first described it
jagged wound; it describes the shape of this opening
